{"parentUuid":"410aa163-72f9-4346-a64d-be39c7edc3ef","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1f81fe877b9073d0","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_017N11EuhP2sJGWFqog7Qc9M","toolUseID":"toolu_017N11EuhP2sJGWFqog7Qc9M","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:17:23.410Z","uuid":"2d9f970f-3c59-4265-9ab8-adb1f3125695","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"2d9f970f-3c59-4265-9ab8-adb1f3125695","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1f81fe877b9073d0","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_017N11EuhP2sJGWFqog7Qc9M","toolUseID":"toolu_017N11EuhP2sJGWFqog7Qc9M","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:17:23.410Z","uuid":"1bf597b9-28ed-42e8-9f98-2484bea7db72","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"2d022ea9-b1c4-402c-93ca-29cd8d8bade3","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"a1f81fe877b9073d0","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017N11EuhP2sJGWFqog7Qc9M","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Welfare-Tons: Mathematical Specification\n     2→\n     3→## The North Star Metric for Jagat Kalyan\n     4→\n     5→**Version**: 2.0\n     6→**Date**: 2026-03-11\n     7→**Author**: John \"Dhyana\" Shrader, with analytical support from Claude\n     8→**Status**: Draft specification -- ready for peer review and pilot calibration\n     9→**Revision note**: v2.0 restructures the formula to a flat 6-factor multiplicative architecture. v1.0 folded permanence into the carbon component and nested employment, agency, and other social indicators inside a composite $S$ multiplier. v2.0 promotes each dimension to a top-level factor: $W = C \\times E \\times A \\times B \\times V \\times P$. The motivation: zero in any dimension yields zero welfare-tons, with no possibility of hiding a deficit inside a composite.\n    10→\n    11→---\n    12→\n    13→## 0. Design Principles\n    14→\n    15→1. **Multiplicative, not additive.** Following the Jain principle *Parasparopagraho Jivanam* (souls render service to one another), welfare is indivisible. Zero in any dimension yields zero welfare-tons. You cannot trade ecological harm for social benefit. You cannot trade community displacement for carbon tonnage.\n    16→\n    17→2. **Zero kills the product.** If a project sequesters carbon but creates no jobs ($E = 0$), the welfare-tons are zero. If a project employs workers but the community never consented ($A = 0$), the welfare-tons are zero. This is the central enforcement mechanism against greenwashing: every dimension must be positive.\n    18→\n    19→3. **Conservative by default.** When data is missing or uncertain, sub-indicators default to their floor value. The metric rewards transparency and measurement, not optimistic self-reporting.\n    20→\n    21→4. **Compatible with existing standards.** The carbon component ($C$) follows Verra VCS and Gold Standard methodology in tCO2e. Employment metrics reference ILO Decent Work indicators. Biodiversity scoring references the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework. Verification architecture is compatible with ICVCM Core Carbon Principles.\n    22→\n    23→5. **Auditable and decomposable.** Every welfare-ton figure can be decomposed into its six factors ($C, E, A, B, V, P$), and every factor into its sub-indicators, with source data cited for each. The composite number is a summary; the components are the substance.\n    24→\n    25→6. **Normalized against a standard offset.** A conventional carbon credit with minimal employment, no community agency process, monoculture planting, satellite-only verification, and moderate permanence produces welfare-tons significantly below its raw tonnage. A community-led, biodiverse, well-verified, permanent restoration project produces welfare-tons 5-10x above the standard offset baseline, capturing value that carbon-only accounting ignores.\n    26→\n    27→---\n    28→\n    29→## 1. Master Formula\n    30→\n    31→$$W = C \\times E \\times A \\times B \\times V \\times P$$\n    32→\n    33→| Symbol | Name | Domain | Interpretation |\n    34→|--------|------|--------|----------------|\n    35→| $W$ | Welfare-tons | $[0, +\\infty)$ | Composite impact in welfare-ton-CO2e units |\n    36→| $C$ | Verified CO2 tons | $[0, +\\infty)$ | Net tCO2e sequestered or avoided per year |\n    37→| $E$ | Employment factor | $[0, E_{max}]$ | Job creation quality and density |\n    38→| $A$ | Community agency factor | $[0, 1]$ | Community consent, ownership, and self-determination |\n    39→| $B$ | Biodiversity co-benefit | $[0.8, 1.5]$ | Restoration type quality based on biodiversity indices |\n    40→| $V$ | Verification confidence | $[0, 1]$ | Trust in the underlying measurements |\n    41→| $P$ | Permanence factor | $[0, 1]$ | Risk-adjusted durability of sequestered carbon |\n    42→\n    43→**Units**: Welfare-tons are denominated in \"wt-CO2e\" to distinguish them from raw carbon tons. The unit is dimensionally equivalent to tCO2e but semantically distinct -- analogous to QALYs (quality-adjusted life years) in health economics, where the \"quality adjustment\" captures social, ecological, and verification dimensions that raw tonnage ignores.\n    44→\n    45→**Reporting rule**: All welfare-ton figures MUST be reported with the full six-factor decomposition alongside the composite number. A welfare-ton figure without its decomposition is incomplete and should not be cited in isolation.\n    46→\n    47→---\n    48→\n    49→## 2. Carbon Component ($C$)\n    50→\n    51→### 2.1 Definition\n    52→\n    53→$C$ is the net annual CO2-equivalent sequestration or avoidance attributable to the project, expressed in metric tons, after applying an additionality adjustment.\n    54→\n    55→$$C = C_{gross} \\times \\alpha_{add}$$\n    56→\n    57→| Symbol | Name | Domain | Definition |\n    58→|--------|------|--------|------------|\n    59→| $C_{gross}$ | Gross sequestration | $[0, +\\infty)$ tCO2e/yr | Total measured CO2e removed or avoided |\n    60→| $\\alpha_{add}$ | Additionality discount | $(0, 1]$ | Discount for counterfactual baseline |\n    61→\n    62→**Note on permanence**: In v1.0, permanence was folded into $C$ as $\\alpha_{perm}$. In v2.0, permanence is a top-level factor ($P$), applied multiplicatively at the same level as employment and biodiversity. This makes permanence risk visible and prevents it from being buried inside the carbon number.\n    63→\n    64→### 2.2 Gross Sequestration Measurement ($C_{gross}$)\n    65→\n    66→$C_{gross}$ is estimated using a three-layer measurement protocol:\n    67→\n    68→**Layer 1: Remote Sensing**\n    69→- Satellite multispectral imagery (Sentinel-2 at 10m, Planet Labs at 3m) for canopy cover, NDVI, and biomass estimation.\n    70→- LiDAR (where available) for above-ground biomass volumetric estimates.\n    71→- SAR for below-canopy biomass in dense forest and mangrove environments.\n    72→- Measurement frequency: Monthly composites, quarterly analysis.\n    73→- Uncertainty: Typically $\\pm$15-30% for above-ground biomass depending on ecosystem type (Chave et al. 2014).\n    74→\n    75→**Layer 2: Ground-Truth Calibration**\n    76→- Stratified random sampling: minimum 1 plot per 10 hectares (Pearson et al. 2007 VCS guidance).\n    77→- Each plot: DBH inventory, allometric biomass equations (species-specific where available).\n    78→- Soil organic carbon: Composite cores at 0-30cm and 30-100cm, laboratory dry combustion analysis.\n    79→- Community-based monitoring: Trained local workers collect plot data, cross-validated against expert surveys at 10% of plots.\n    80→\n    81→**Layer 3: Temporal Modeling**\n    82→- Bayesian hierarchical model incorporating remote sensing time series, ground-truth calibrations, and climate covariates.\n    83→- Reported value: Conservative estimate at the 80th percentile lower bound (80% probability that true sequestration exceeds the reported value), following the Verra VCS conservativeness principle.\n    84→\n    85→**Carbon Pool Coverage**:\n    86→\n    87→| Pool | Included | Method |\n    88→|------|----------|--------|\n    89→| Above-ground biomass | Yes | Remote sensing + plot inventory |\n    90→| Below-ground biomass | Yes | Root:shoot ratios |\n    91→| Soil organic carbon | Yes (ag/grassland/wetland) | Soil cores |\n    92→| Dead wood | Optional | Plot inventory if significant |\n    93→| Litter | Excluded | Minor pool, high measurement cost |\n    94→| Avoided emissions | Yes, if applicable | Baseline scenario modeling |\n    95→\n    96→### 2.3 Additionality Discount ($\\alpha_{add}$)\n    97→\n    98→Additionality tests whether sequestration would have occurred without the project. This is the most epistemically challenging component.\n    99→\n   100→$$\\alpha_{add} = 1 - P_{baseline}(\\text{sequestration occurs anyway})$$"}]},"uuid":"b152e662-5cc8-4456-a7a0-d36b459cc50c","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:17:23.410Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"2d022ea9-b1c4-402c-93ca-29cd8d8bade3","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
