{"parentUuid":"c3fb74e8-0161-4362-82d4-0a7df5551dff","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1f81fe877b9073d0","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01GW8CS57hxjSVS9F7M9sqA3","toolUseID":"toolu_01GW8CS57hxjSVS9F7M9sqA3","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:17:29.025Z","uuid":"cc846b41-0f3e-4440-8e5e-fe62dad4542a","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"cc846b41-0f3e-4440-8e5e-fe62dad4542a","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1f81fe877b9073d0","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01GW8CS57hxjSVS9F7M9sqA3","toolUseID":"toolu_01GW8CS57hxjSVS9F7M9sqA3","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:17:29.025Z","uuid":"6052ad89-77b4-4535-a15d-b779b1f295e7","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"d537bf1b-801e-42c5-8fe3-bba77db725f2","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"a1f81fe877b9073d0","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GW8CS57hxjSVS9F7M9sqA3","type":"tool_result","content":"   100→$$\\alpha_{add} = 1 - P_{baseline}(\\text{sequestration occurs anyway})$$\n   101→\n   102→**Three-part test** (adapted from CDM and Gold Standard):\n   103→\n   104→**Test 1: Regulatory surplus.** Would the activity be required by law regardless of carbon finance? If yes: $\\alpha_{add} \\leq 0.3$.\n   105→\n   106→**Test 2: Financial additionality.** Is the project financially viable without carbon revenue? Compare project IRR with and without. If viable without carbon: $\\alpha_{add} = 0.5$.\n   107→\n   108→**Test 3: Barrier analysis.** Score three barriers:\n   109→\n   110→| Barrier | Weight | Score range |\n   111→|---------|--------|-------------|\n   112→| Financial (access to capital) | 0.40 | 0 (none) to 1 (severe) |\n   113→| Institutional (governance, permits) | 0.30 | 0 to 1 |\n   114→| Technical (knowledge, capacity) | 0.30 | 0 to 1 |\n   115→\n   116→$\\alpha_{add} = 0.5 + 0.5 \\times \\text{barrier\\_score}$, range $[0.5, 1.0]$.\n   117→\n   118→**Combined**: $\\alpha_{add} = \\max(\\text{Test1}, \\text{Test2}, \\text{Test3})$, using the strongest evidence of additionality.\n   119→\n   120→**Reference values**:\n   121→\n   122→| Scenario | $\\alpha_{add}$ |\n   123→|----------|-----------------|\n   124→| Degraded land, no alternative use | 0.95 |\n   125→| Former agricultural land in transition | 0.80 |\n   126→| Forest in region with active deforestation | 0.70 |\n   127→| Urban greening in mandated sustainability zone | 0.40 |\n   128→\n   129→---\n   130→\n   131→## 3. Employment Factor ($E$)\n   132→\n   133→### 3.1 Definition\n   134→\n   135→$E$ measures the density and quality of jobs created per unit of investment, normalized so that the target of 50+ jobs per $1M invested at 1.5x minimum wage receives an $E$ value in the range that drives the 5-10x amplification.\n   136→\n   137→$$E = E_{density} \\times E_{quality}$$\n   138→\n   139→### 3.2 Employment Density ($E_{density}$)\n   140→\n   141→$E_{density}$ measures jobs created per $1M invested, normalized against the target of 50 jobs/$1M.\n   142→\n   143→**Raw metric**: $j = \\text{FTE jobs created} / (\\text{total investment in \\$M})$\n   144→\n   145→**Continuous scoring**:\n   146→\n   147→$$E_{density} = \\frac{\\min(j, \\; j_{cap})}{j_{ref}}$$\n   148→\n   149→where:\n   150→- $j_{ref} = 25$ (the reference point: a standard carbon offset with minimal employment generates roughly 25 jobs per $1M, based on ILO forestry employment data)\n   151→- $j_{cap} = 100$ (cap to prevent extreme values from projects with very low capital intensity)\n   152→\n   153→This yields:\n   154→\n   155→| Jobs per $1M | $E_{density}$ | Interpretation |\n   156→|---------------|----------------|----------------|\n   157→| 0 | 0 | No employment -- **kills the product** |\n   158→| 10 | 0.40 | Low density (large-scale mechanized) |\n   159→| 25 | 1.00 | Reference (standard offset baseline) |\n   160→| 50 | 2.00 | Target (labor-intensive restoration) |\n   161→| 75 | 3.00 | High density (community cooperative) |\n   162→| 100+ | 4.00 | Maximum (capped) |\n   163→\n   164→**Why the cap matters**: Without it, a project could inflate $E_{density}$ by hiring 500 people for trivial tasks. The cap at 100 jobs/$1M, combined with the wage quality floor (below), prevents this. At $1M investment, 100 jobs at 1.5x minimum wage in a developing economy consumes essentially the entire budget in payroll -- any higher and the numbers are implausible or the wages are poverty-level.\n   165→\n   166→### 3.3 Employment Quality ($E_{quality}$)\n   167→\n   168→$E_{quality}$ captures whether the jobs are decent work, not just headcount. It integrates three sub-dimensions:\n   169→\n   170→$$E_{quality} = q_{wage} \\times q_{local} \\times q_{duration}$$\n   171→\n   172→#### 3.3.1 Wage Quality ($q_{wage}$)\n   173→\n   174→The wage floor is a hard constraint: projects paying below 1.5x local minimum wage receive a steep penalty.\n   175→\n   176→$$q_{wage} = \\begin{cases} 0.3 & \\text{if } w < 1.0 \\times MW \\\\[6pt] 0.3 + 0.7 \\times \\dfrac{w/MW - 1.0}{0.5} & \\text{if } 1.0 \\leq w/MW < 1.5 \\\\[6pt] 1.0 + 0.25 \\times \\min\\left(\\dfrac{w/MW - 1.5}{1.0}, \\; 1.0\\right) & \\text{if } w/MW \\geq 1.5 \\end{cases}$$\n   177→\n   178→where $w$ is the average worker wage and $MW$ is the local minimum wage (PPP-adjusted for cross-country comparisons).\n   179→\n   180→| Wage / Minimum Wage | $q_{wage}$ | Note |\n   181→|----------------------|------------|------|\n   182→| < 1.0x | 0.30 | Severe penalty; likely disqualifying |\n   183→| 1.0x | 0.30 | At minimum wage -- still penalized |\n   184→| 1.25x | 0.65 | Below target floor |\n   185→| 1.5x (target floor) | 1.00 | Meets Jagat Kalyan standard |\n   186→| 2.0x | 1.125 | Good wages |\n   187→| 2.5x+ | 1.25 | Excellent wages (capped) |\n   188→\n   189→**Anti-gaming mechanism**: The wage floor is non-negotiable. A project cannot hire 200 workers at $0.50/day to inflate $E_{density}$ because $q_{wage} = 0.30$ would crush the product. The interaction $E_{density} \\times q_{wage}$ means you need BOTH quantity AND quality. Specifically: 100 workers at below-minimum wage yields $E = 4.0 \\times 0.30 \\times q_{local} \\times q_{duration} \\approx 1.2$ at best, which is worse than 50 workers at 1.5x minimum ($E = 2.0 \\times 1.0 \\times q_{local} \\times q_{duration} \\approx 2.0$). The math rewards quality over raw headcount.\n   190→\n   191→#### 3.3.2 Local Labor ($q_{local}$)\n   192→\n   193→$$q_{local} = 0.5 + 0.5 \\times f_{local}$$\n   194→\n   195→where $f_{local}$ is the fraction of workers who are local residents (defined as residing within 50 km of the project site for at least 12 months prior to employment).\n   196→\n   197→| Fraction local | $q_{local}$ |\n   198→|----------------|-------------|\n   199→| 0% | 0.50 |\n   200→| 50% | 0.75 |\n   201→| 90% | 0.95 |\n   202→| 100% | 1.00 |\n   203→\n   204→#### 3.3.3 Employment Duration ($q_{duration}$)\n   205→\n   206→$$q_{duration} = 0.5 + 0.5 \\times \\min\\left(\\frac{d}{12}, \\; 1.0\\right)$$\n   207→\n   208→where $d$ is the average contract duration in months.\n   209→\n   210→| Duration | $q_{duration}$ |\n   211→|----------|----------------|\n   212→| Seasonal, 3 months | 0.625 |\n   213→| 6 months | 0.75 |\n   214→| 12+ months | 1.00 |\n   215→\n   216→### 3.4 Composite $E$ Calculation\n   217→\n   218→$$E = E_{density} \\times E_{quality} = \\frac{\\min(j, \\; 100)}{25} \\times q_{wage} \\times q_{local} \\times q_{duration}$$\n   219→\n   220→**Theoretical bounds**:\n   221→- Minimum: $E = 0$ (no jobs created)\n   222→- Baseline (standard offset): $E \\approx 1.0$ (25 jobs/$1M at reference wages)\n   223→- Target: $E \\approx 2.0$ (50 jobs/$1M at 1.5x MW, local, year-round)\n   224→- Maximum: $E = 4.0 \\times 1.25 \\times 1.0 \\times 1.0 = 5.0$\n   225→\n   226→### 3.5 Data Collection Requirements\n   227→\n   228→| Data point | Source | Frequency | Verification |\n   229→|------------|--------|-----------|--------------|\n   230→| FTE job count | Payroll records | Monthly | Cross-check with tax filings and site visits |\n   231→| Total investment | Financial statements | Annual | Third-party audit |\n   232→| Average wage | Payroll records (disaggregated) | Monthly | Comparison to national MW database |\n   233→| Worker residence | Employment contracts + ID verification | At hire | Random spot-check by assessor |\n   234→| Contract duration | Employment contracts | At hire + renewal | HR records audit |\n   235→\n   236→---\n   237→\n   238→## 4. Community Agency Factor ($A$)\n   239→\n   240→### 4.1 Definition\n   241→\n   242→$A$ measures whether the community chose the project. It is a consent protocol score on $[0, 1]$ with a clear interpretation: $A = 0$ means the community was not consulted, and the project earns zero welfare-tons. $A = 1$ means the community initiated and governs the project.\n   243→\n   244→This factor operationalizes Free, Prior, and Informed Consent (FPIC) as articulated by the UN Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples and the IFC Performance Standards.\n   245→\n   246→### 4.2 Scoring Rubric\n   247→\n   248→$A$ is the weighted sum of four dimensions, each scored on $[0, 1]$:\n   249→"}]},"uuid":"c96a6b81-2d8d-4dc3-88d2-68023fd69787","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:17:29.025Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"d537bf1b-801e-42c5-8fe3-bba77db725f2","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
