{"parentUuid":"91040c21-d630-4609-a950-671da98406dd","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1f81fe877b9073d0","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_014P53muDZHHJbaEeKT3rSRW","toolUseID":"toolu_014P53muDZHHJbaEeKT3rSRW","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:17:41.089Z","uuid":"482b2735-3f87-4a87-b8dd-c04cdfdd1a52","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"482b2735-3f87-4a87-b8dd-c04cdfdd1a52","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1f81fe877b9073d0","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_014P53muDZHHJbaEeKT3rSRW","toolUseID":"toolu_014P53muDZHHJbaEeKT3rSRW","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:17:41.089Z","uuid":"f9fa1b34-faf3-4c4b-ac18-0025d353bb04","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"7db50fd4-b712-451f-8750-405090a50ce8","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"a1f81fe877b9073d0","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014P53muDZHHJbaEeKT3rSRW","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Carbon Attribution Feasibility Study\n     2→\n     3→**Jagat Kalyan: Per-Inference Carbon Attribution for AI-Coordinated Ecological Restoration**\n     4→\n     5→Version 1.0 | March 2026\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Executive Summary\n    10→\n    11→Jagat Kalyan's core innovation is **per-inference carbon attribution** -- tagging every AI API call with its marginal ecological cost, then routing offset demand into verified ecological restoration. This document assesses the technical feasibility, market opportunity, and implementation pathway for this approach.\n    12→\n    13→**Bottom line**: Per-inference carbon attribution is feasible today at the estimation level (within +/-40% accuracy), achievable at higher precision within 6 months using real-time grid data and open-source tooling, and could reach provider-verified accuracy within 2 years contingent on industry partnerships. The voluntary carbon market is growing rapidly enough (CAGR 35-50%) to absorb AI-offset demand, and emerging standards (ISO/IEC 21031, GSF SCI for AI) provide regulatory tailwinds.\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## 1. Per-Inference Energy Consumption\n    18→\n    19→### 1.1 Known Energy Benchmarks\n    20→\n    21→The energy cost of a single AI inference varies by model, prompt length, output length, and hardware. Published and estimated benchmarks as of early 2026:\n    22→\n    23→| Model | Energy per Query (Wh) | Source / Basis |\n    24→|-------|----------------------|----------------|\n    25→| Google Search (baseline) | ~0.30 | Google disclosures |\n    26→| Google Gemini (text) | ~0.24 | Google environmental report |\n    27→| ChatGPT (GPT-4o, short) | ~0.34-0.42 | OpenAI disclosures; Epoch AI analysis |\n    28→| ChatGPT (GPT-4o, typical) | ~0.42 | Epoch AI (Feb 2025 revision) |\n    29→| Claude 3 Haiku | ~0.22 | Public benchmarks (estimated) |\n    30→| Claude 3.7 Sonnet | ~0.5-1.5 | Estimated range; no official disclosure |\n    31→| Claude 3 Opus (~400 tokens) | ~4.05 | Public benchmarks (estimated) |\n    32→| Reasoning models (o1, R1) | ~10-20 | 30-50x base model; extended chain-of-thought |\n    33→\n    34→**Key observations:**\n    35→\n    36→- There is roughly a 100x range between the cheapest inference (small model, short query) and the most expensive (large reasoning model, long output).\n    37→- Reasoning models (OpenAI o1, DeepSeek R1) consume 30-50x more energy than standard models because they generate extensive internal reasoning chains before producing output.\n    38→- Anthropic does not publicly disclose per-inference energy figures for Claude. Estimates for Claude 3.7 Sonnet range from 0.5 to 1.5 Wh depending on output length. The 0.95 Wh figure cited in some analyses is a reasonable midpoint estimate for a typical ~500-token exchange.\n    39→- All figures are pre-PUE (facility overhead not included).\n    40→\n    41→### 1.2 Variance Factors\n    42→\n    43→Energy per inference is not a fixed number. It varies along several dimensions:\n    44→\n    45→**Model size**: Roughly proportional to parameter count for autoregressive generation. A 70B model uses approximately 10x the compute of a 7B model per token. Mixture-of-experts architectures (Mixtral, GPT-4) activate only a subset of parameters, reducing this proportionality.\n    46→\n    47→**Prompt length (input tokens)**: The prefill phase processes all input tokens in parallel. Energy scales roughly linearly with prompt length but is amortized across the full response. A 10,000-token prompt costs more than a 100-token prompt, but not 100x more, because the generation phase dominates for long outputs.\n    48→\n    49→**Output length (generated tokens)**: The primary energy driver. Each output token requires a full forward pass through the model. A 2,000-token response costs roughly 10x a 200-token response in generation energy.\n    50→\n    51→**Hardware**: NVIDIA H100 GPUs are roughly 2-3x more energy-efficient per FLOP than A100s. Google TPUv5 shows similar generational improvements. Older hardware in non-hyperscaler data centers may be 5-10x less efficient than cutting-edge chips.\n    52→\n    53→**Batch size and utilization**: High-throughput serving (batched inference) amortizes fixed costs. A GPU running at 90% utilization is far more energy-efficient per inference than one at 20%. This is a major source of variance between providers.\n    54→\n    55→### 1.3 Data Center PUE (Power Usage Effectiveness)\n    56→\n    57→PUE measures total facility energy divided by IT equipment energy. A PUE of 1.2 means 20% overhead for cooling, networking, lighting, and other infrastructure.\n    58→\n    59→| Operator | PUE (2025) | Notes |\n    60→|----------|-----------|-------|\n    61→| Google | 1.09 | Industry-leading; trailing 12-month average |\n    62→| AWS | 1.15 | Global average; best site 1.04 (Europe) |\n    63→| Microsoft Azure | 1.11-1.35 | Range across facilities; best in Wyoming |\n    64→| Industry average | 1.54 | Uptime Institute 2025 survey |\n    65→| Enterprise (non-hyperscale) | 1.5-1.8 | Older facilities |\n    66→\n    67→**Implication for attribution**: The PUE multiplier adds 9-80% to raw compute energy depending on the data center. For hyperscaler-hosted models (Claude, GPT, Gemini), a PUE of 1.1-1.2 is appropriate. For self-hosted or enterprise deployments, 1.4-1.8 is more realistic.\n    68→\n    69→### 1.4 Marginal vs. Average Cost\n    70→\n    71→The fundamental measurement challenge: does an additional inference consume marginal energy (the cost of one more query on an already-running GPU) or average energy (total facility energy / total queries)?\n    72→\n    73→- **Marginal cost** is lower because GPUs are already powered on and partially utilized. Adding one query to a batch barely changes total power draw.\n    74→- **Average cost** captures the proportional share of all overhead, including idle time between queries, redundant capacity, and cooling.\n    75→- **For attribution purposes**, average cost is more appropriate because it reflects the true resource consumption allocated to each inference. Marginal cost would undercount by ignoring shared infrastructure.\n    76→\n    77→EcoLogits and similar tools use average cost estimation, which is the correct approach for carbon attribution.\n    78→\n    79→---\n    80→"}]},"uuid":"14ff13f7-0c3b-4f35-9a7e-6f7342f2741e","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:17:41.089Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"7db50fd4-b712-451f-8750-405090a50ce8","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
